\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Linear Advection Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest initial-value problem (IVP) is given by the first-order partial
 differential equation (PDE) with a constant coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{u}{t}+a\pdv{u}{x}=0\qc t>0\qc x\in(-\infty,\infty)
\]

\end_inset

and the initial condition (IC)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(t=0,x)=u^{0}(x)\qc x\in(-\infty,\infty)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The characteristic curve of the PDE passing through 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t^{0},x^{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the solution of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{x}{t}=a\qc x(t=0)=x^{0}
\]

\end_inset

which is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=at+x^{0}
\]

\end_inset

If we treat 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{0}$
\end_inset

 as a varying parameter, then all of the characteristic curves together
 form a one-parameter family of parallel straight lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,x)$
\end_inset

 plane.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The characteristic curves of the linear advection equation are straight
 lines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Along any characteristic curve, the rate of change of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{u}{t}=\pdv{u}{t}+\dv{x}{t}\pdv{u}{x}=0
\]

\end_inset

which means 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 remains constant along a characteristic curve.
 The solution of the IVP is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(t,x)=u^{0}\left(x^{0}\right)=u^{0}(x-at)
\]

\end_inset

The physical meaning of this solution is a wave packet moving with constant
 speed 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, whose shape keeps unchanged.
 This is why it is called the 
\noun on
linear advection equation
\noun default
 or the 
\noun on
single wave equation
\noun default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Systems of Linear Hyperbolic PDEs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A system of first-order linear PDEs with two independent variables 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is generally written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{u_{i}}{t}+\sum_{j=1}^{m}a_{ij}\pdv{u_{j}}{x}=0
\]

\end_inset

or in matrix form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{U}_{t}+\Matrix{A}\ket{U}_{x}=\ket{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coefficient matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

 determines the behavior of the system.
 This can be seen from the analysis of the following eigenvalue problems.
 For simplicity, we will assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

 to be 
\emph on
constant
\emph default
 in this section.
 The more general cases, in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

 could depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 or even 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

, will be discussed in the section of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "subsec:Systems-of-Quasilinear-Hyperbolic-PDEs"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
If a scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, a row vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra{L}$
\end_inset

 and a column vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{R}$
\end_inset

 together satisfy the following equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bra{L}\Matrix{A}=\bra{L}\lambda\qc\Matrix{A}\ket{R}=\lambda\ket{R}
\]

\end_inset

then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is an 
\noun on
eigenvalue
\noun default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bra{L}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\noun on
left eigenvector
\noun default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\noun on
right eigenvector
\noun default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
If all of the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

 are real numbers and there are 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 linearly independent (left/right) eigenvectors, then the system of PDEs
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{U}_{t}+\Matrix{A}\ket{U}_{x}=\ket{0}
\]

\end_inset

 is said to be 
\noun on
hyperbolic
\noun default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a hyperbolic systems, we can collect the right and left eigenvectors
 into two matrices:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Matrix{R}:=\begin{bmatrix}\ket{R_{1}} & \cdots & \ket{R_{m}}\end{bmatrix}\qc\Matrix{L}:=\begin{bmatrix}\bra{L_{1}}\\
\vdots\\
\bra{L_{m}}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

They are both invertible, since all of their columns and rows are linearly
 independent, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

 can be diagonalised:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Matrix{A}\Matrix{R}=\Matrix{R}\Matrix{\Lambda}\implies\Matrix{A}=\Matrix{R}\Matrix{\Lambda}\Matrix{R}^{-1}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Matrix{L}\Matrix{A}=\Matrix{\Lambda}\Matrix{L}\implies\Matrix{A}=\Matrix{L}^{-1}\Matrix{\Lambda}\Matrix{L}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By define a set of 
\noun on
characteristic variables
\noun default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{V}:=\Matrix{L}\ket{U}=\begin{bmatrix}\braket{L_{1}}{U}\\
\vdots\\
\braket{L_{m}}{U}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

the original system
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{U}_{t}+\Matrix{A}\ket{U}_{x}=\ket{0}
\]

\end_inset

can be decoupled as 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 independent linear advection equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{V}_{t}+\Matrix{\Lambda}\ket{V}_{x}=\ket{0}\implies\pdv{v_{i}}{t}+\lambda_{i}\pdv{v_{i}}{x}\qc i=1,\dots,m
\]

\end_inset

which is is called the 
\noun on
canonical form
\noun default
 or 
\noun on
characteristic form
\noun default
 of system.
 Each of them can be solved along its characteristic curve
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{x}{t}=\lambda_{i}\qc x(t=0)=x^{0}\implies x-\lambda_{i}t=x^{0}
\]

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{i}(t,x)=v_{i}^{0}(x-\lambda_{i}t)
\]

\end_inset

which can be transformed back to the original variables 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{U}=\Matrix{L}^{-1}\ket{V}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nonlinear Hyperbolic PDEs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Burgers Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the (phase) speed is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, then the PDE becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{u}{t}+a(u)\pdv{u}{x}=0\qc t>0\qc x\in(-\infty,\infty)
\]

\end_inset

which is called the 
\noun on
quasilinear wave equation
\noun default
.
 More specifically, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a(u)=ku$
\end_inset

, then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{u}{t}+ku\pdv{u}{x}=0
\]

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

, it is called the 
\noun on
Burgers equation.

\noun default
 We will keep writing the coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 even if it is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, since the conservative variable 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 may be any physical quantity, but the wave speed 
\begin_inset Formula $ku$
\end_inset

 must has a dimension of speed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The initial condition (IC) is generally given as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(t=0,x)=u^{0}(x)\qc x\in(-\infty,\infty)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the quasilinear wave equation is the nonlinearized version of the
 linear advection equation, we can try to solve it, at least locally, as
 what we have done for its linear counterpart.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The characteristic curve of the PDE passing through 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t^{0},x^{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the solution of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{x}{t}=a(u)\qc x(t=0)=x^{0}
\]

\end_inset

which is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=a(u)t+x^{0}
\]

\end_inset

If we treat 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{0}$
\end_inset

 as a varying parameter, then all of the characteristic curves together
 form a one-parameter family of curves in 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,x)$
\end_inset

 plane.
 However, they are generally no longer parallel to each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first assume that before a critical time 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{*}$
\end_inset

, the characteristic curves do not intersect with each other.
 Along any characteristic curve, 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 still keeps unchanged
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{u}{t}=\pdv{u}{t}+\dv{x}{t}\pdv{u}{x}=\pdv{u}{t}+a\pdv{u}{x}=0
\]

\end_inset

The solution of the PDE is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(t,x)=u^{0}(x-a(u)t)
\]

\end_inset

from which 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 can be solved in general, not necessarily in a closed form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The characteristic curves of the quasilinear wave equation are straight
 lines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One question is how long does the classical solution stand valid? The answer
 is it depends on the positiveness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{a}{u}\dv{u^{0}}{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us first assume 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 smooth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{a}{u}\dv{u^{0}}{x}>0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(0)<x_{2}(0)\implies\forall t>0\colon x_{1}(t)<x_{2}(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Using the definition of characteristic curves, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{x_{i}}{t}=a\left(u(t,x_{i})\right)$
\end_inset

, and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 remains unchanged along the characteristic curves, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(t,x_{i})=u^{0}(x_{i}(0))$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{\left(x_{2}-x_{1}\right)}{t}=a\left(u^{0}\left(x_{2}(0)\right)\right)-a\left(u^{0}\left(x_{1}(0)\right)\right)>0
\]

\end_inset

Geometrically, in this case, the characteristic curves diverge from each
 other as 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{a}{u}\dv{u^{0}}{x}<0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(0)<x_{2}(0)\implies$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\exists t^{*}>0:x_{1}(t^{*})=x_{2}(t^{*})\qand\forall t\in(0,t^{*})\colon x_{1}(t)<x_{2}(t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The proof is similar to the previous theorem, but
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{\left(x_{2}-x_{1}\right)}{t}=a\left(u^{0}\left(x_{2}(0)\right)\right)-a\left(u^{0}\left(x_{1}(0)\right)\right)<0
\]

\end_inset

Geometrically, in this case, the characteristic curves converge to each
 other as 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 increases.
 Since they are both straight lines, they will finally (at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{*}>0$
\end_inset

) intersect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When two characteristic curves intersect, 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 will have two values
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=u^{0}\left(x_{1}(0)\right)\qand u=u^{0}\left(x_{2}(0)\right)
\]

\end_inset

which are generally inconsistent.
 This means a discontinuity has arised, although the IC is smooth.
 This will never happen for a linear PDE, such as the linear advection equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Among all the intersecting time 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{*}$
\end_inset

, the minimum one is called the 
\noun on
breaking time
\noun default
, denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{b}$
\end_inset

, at which the classical solution breaks and becomes invalid afterwards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
What will happen after the breaking? If we think of 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(t^{b},x\right)$
\end_inset

 as the IC of a new IVP, it will become a Riemann problem, which will be
 discussed in the following sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Systems of Quasilinear Hyperbolic PDEs
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Systems-of-Quasilinear-Hyperbolic-PDEs"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A system of first-order quasilinear PDEs with two independent variables
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is generally written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{u_{i}}{t}+\sum_{j=1}^{m}a_{ij}(t,x,u_{1},\cdots,u_{m})\pdv{u_{j}}{x}+b_{i}(t,x,u_{1},\cdots,u_{m})=0
\]

\end_inset

or in matrix form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{U}_{t}+\Matrix{A}\ket{U}_{x}+\ket{B}=\ket{0}
\]

\end_inset

in which, the coefficient matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A}$
\end_inset

 determines the behavior of the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many systems of first-order nonlinear PDEs can be transformed into this
 form.
 For example, the system of conservation laws
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{U}_{t}+\ket{F}_{x}=\ket{0}\qc\ket{U}=\begin{bmatrix}u_{1}\\
\vdots\\
u_{m}
\end{bmatrix}\qc\ket{F}=\begin{bmatrix}f_{1}(u_{1},\cdots,u_{m})\\
\vdots\\
f_{m}(u_{1},\cdots,u_{m})
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

can be transformed into the quasilinear form with the 
\noun on
Jacobian matrix
\noun default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Matrix{A}:=\pdv{F}{U}=\begin{bmatrix}\pdv{f_{1}}{u_{1}} & \cdots & \pdv{f_{1}}{u_{m}}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots\\
\pdv{f_{m}}{u_{1}} & \cdots & \pdv{f_{m}}{u_{m}}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

as the coefficient matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discontinuities and Weak Solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous section, we have seen that even with a smooth IC, the smooth
 solution of a nonlinear PDE can finally become discontinuous.
 To handle such cases, we have to extend the notion of solution to a weaker
 sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Conservation Laws
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of the nonlinear PDEs coming from physics can be formulated as conservation
s laws, i.e.
 the law of conservation of some physical quatity (mass, momentum, angular
 momentum, energy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $V^{C}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\noun on
control volume
\noun default
 in space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V^{C}$
\end_inset

 is the boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, which is moving with a velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{C}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the 
\noun on
density
\noun default
 of some physical quantity, i.e.
 something per unit volume.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 is the velocity of a fluid particle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{f}:=\phi\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\noun on
flux
\noun default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 how much 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 pass through a 
\emph on
fixed
\emph default
 surface per unit area in unit time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, the 
\noun on
conservation law
\noun default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\MDV{}{t}\int_{V^{C}}\phi\dd{V}=\int_{V^{C}}\pdv{\phi}{t}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V^{C}}\vec{f}\cdot\vu{n}\dd{S}=0}
\]

\end_inset

which is usually used for fixed control volumes, or
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\MDV{}{t}\int_{V^{C}}\phi\dd{V}=\dv{t}\int_{V^{C}}\phi\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V^{C}}\left(\vec{f}-\phi\vec{u}^{C}\right)\cdot\vu{n}\dd{S}}
\]

\end_inset

which is usually used for moving control volumes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{f}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 smooth with respect to spatial variables, we can apply Gauss's divergence
 theorem, which leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\pdv{\phi}{t}+\div\vec{f}=0}
\]

\end_inset

However, if the 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 smooth prerequisite is not satisfied, we should go back to the integral
 form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Discontinuity Condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose there is a discontinuity surface 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 moving with velocity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{u}^{S}=\vu{e}_{\perp}u_{\perp}^{S}+\vu{e}_{\parallel}u_{\parallel}^{S}
\]

\end_inset

Choose a cylindrical control volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{C}$
\end_inset

, which satisfies the following requirements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It has an infinitesimal height 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

, formulas can be simplified, since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{h\to0}\vec{u}^{C}=\vec{u}^{S}\qc\lim_{h\to0}\dv{t}\int_{V^{C}}\phi\dd{V}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
All of its walls are 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is sandwiched between the top 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{+}$
\end_inset

 (on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\vu{n}=\vu{e}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

) and the bottom 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{-}$
\end_inset

 (on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\vu{n}=-\vu{e}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{C}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{+}\parallel S\parallel S_{-}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, the conservation law is reduced to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{h\to0}\oint_{\partial V}\left(\vec{f}-\phi\vec{u}^{S}\right)\cdot\vu{n}\dd{S}=\int_{S_{+}\cup S_{-}}\left(\vec{f}-\phi\vec{u}^{S}\right)\cdot\vu{n}\dd{S}
\]

\end_inset

Replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\vu{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm\vu{e}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{S_{\pm}}\dd{S}\to0$
\end_inset

, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{u_{\perp}^{S}=\frac{f_{+}-f_{-}}{\phi_{+}-\phi_{-}}\qc f_{\pm}=\lim_{h\to\pm0}\vec{f}\cdot\vu{e}_{\perp}}
\]

\end_inset

which is called the 
\noun on
jump condition
\noun default
 aka the 
\noun on
Rankine–Hugoniot condition
\noun default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Weak Solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Riemann Problems
